Package me.wobblyyyy.edt

Interface Arrayable<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element that's stored in the array.
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    DynamicArray, DynamicBoolean, DynamicDouble, DynamicFloat, DynamicInteger, DynamicString, FrozenArray, StaticArray, StaticBoolean, StaticDouble, StaticFloat, StaticInteger, StaticString
    public interface Arrayable<E>
    An interface to be shared by all implementations of the core array concept that much of edt is based on.

        E get​(int index)
        Get a value from the array based on a provided index.
        Parameters:
        index - the index to query a value from.
        Returns:
        the value that comes from the index. If the index is out of the array's bounds, we don't do anything - an exception is thrown anyways, so we don't need to return anything.

      • indexOf

        int indexOf​(E value)
        Get the index of a specified element. This method searches the entire active array and attempts to find the index of the first instance of that object. If that object is stored in the array multiple times, only the first index will be returned.
        Parameters:
        value - the element to query. This element should be exactly the same as any of the elements that may be found. If this element isn't the same as any of the elements contained in the array, we return -1.
        Returns:
        if the queried element is contained within the predefined range of (0) to (array max), return the index of the first instance of the queried element. If the queried element is not contained within the given range, return -1.
        See Also:
        DynamicArray.indexOfInRange(Object, int, int)

      • isEmpty

        boolean isEmpty()
        Check to see if the entire array is empty. The array being empty is defined by the active size of the array being equal to zero.
        Returns:
        whether or not the array is entirely empty.

      • contains

        boolean contains​(E value)
        Check to see if the array contains any instances of the queried element. If an instance of the element is found, this method will return true. If no instances of the element are found, this method will return false.

        This method works by attempting to find the index of the queried element. If the index is -1, we know the element isn't contained in the array, and we return false. If the index is 0 or above, however, we know that the element is contained somewhere in the array - thus, we return true.

        Parameters:
        value - the element to query.
        Returns:
        true if the queried element is found inside of the array at some point, false if it isn't.
        See Also:
        DynamicArray.indexOf(Object), DynamicArray.isEmpty()

      • checkIndex

        boolean checkIndex​(int index)
        Check to see if the requested index is a valid part of the internal array used by the Arrayable element in question.
        Parameters:
        index - the index to check.
        Returns:
        true if the index is contained in the active size of the array. False if the index isn't contained in the active size of the array.

      • toArrayList

        java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.Object> toArrayList()
        Convert this instance of an array into an instance of an ArrayList. This method calls the toArray() method in order to convert the internal facing array into an external facing one, and then creates a new ArrayList instance based on the converted array.
        Returns:
        a newly-created ArrayList instance, composed of the same elements as the calling array.

      • toArray

        java.lang.Object[] toArray()
        Convert this instance of an array into a plain array instance by creating a clone of the elements contained in the calling instance that is the same size as the active size.

        The internally-stored array is often larger than the external-facing array for performance reasons - although it uses more memory, it takes less CPU power to store un-used array values even when they aren't accessible to the user. This means that the returned array here isn't exactly the same as the array that's used inside of this class.

        Returns:
        the elements of the array, in array form. This is a new array, not the same array - you can't modify this array and expect the values contained in the internally-used array to be updated, as this method is intentionally immutable.

      • toArray

        E[] toArray​(E[] base)
        Get the array of objects contained in the array and cast them into a given array. Please note: number types CAN NOT be cast here. In order to get an array of numbers, you need to use the methods linked in the see tags of this method.
        Parameters:
        base - the base array - this array will be over-written by a copied array, originating from the internal array.
        Returns:
        the internally-stored array of elements, cast into a given array of the type E.

      • toDoubleArray

        java.lang.Double[] toDoubleArray()
        Get the array's internal array and cast it into a number array. This method is rather expensive, as it has to manually unbox each of the objects contained inside of the array.
        Returns:
        a pre-casted array of double elements.

      • toIntegerArray

        java.lang.Integer[] toIntegerArray()
        Get the array's internal array and cast it into a number array. This method is rather expensive, as it has to manually unbox each of the objects contained inside of the array.
        Returns:
        a pre-casted array of integer elements.

      • itr

        ItrSingle<E> itr()
        Get the array's iterator nested class. The iterator class provides iteration functionality for the array data structure. Documentation on the iterator class's functionality is available in the iterator class itself - take a look at the "see" tags on this JavaDoc if you're confused.
        Returns:
        this array's iterator nested class. This class is generated at the array's construction and does not need to be maintained or interacted with other than to iterate over the array of elements.
